FT  06 FEB 92 / UK News (Employment): Disabled quota not being met
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ONLY ONE government department out of a total of 29 is meeting a quota of 3
per cent for the employment of registered disabled people, official figures
published yesterday show.
The Civil Service is not bound by the same law that requires other employers
to meet the quota but says it tries to meet the standard voluntarily. About
22 per cent of employers overall are estimated to meet the quota.
The figures show that 3.2 per cent of the Department of Employment's
workforce is registered disabled. The overall average for government
departments is 1.4 per cent.
The analysis, published by the Department of Employment in Employment
Gazette, also shows that only 12 district councils in England and Wales out
of 366, and none of 47 county councils or 33 London boroughs, meet the
quota. In Scotland, two districts out of 53, but none of the nine regional
or three island councils meet the 3 per cent figure.
Other nationalised and public authorities not meeting the quota, according
to the figures are the BBC, BR, the Civil Aviation Authority, British Coal
and the Post Office.
The government says the figures are distorted because many disabled people
prefer not to register. It added that the number of disabled people had
declined and it was no longer possible for organisations to meet the 3 per
cent quota.
</TEXT>
