FT  06 FEB 92 / Subsidies urged for coalmining
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Coalfield Communities Campaign, a local-authority pressure group,
yesterday called for European Community subsidies to keep the UK coal
industry alive.
The group wants a moratorium on pit closures while ways are found to support
the industry.
MEPs with coalmining interests have joined forces with the local authorities
in seeking a moratorium on closures in the face of continued threats of more
closures.
Mr Stephen Fothergill, the campaign's national director, said: 'UK mining
communities deserve a breathing space and the miners themselves deserve
recognition for their magnificent achievement in doubling production.'
This is the last full year before the expiry of a contract between the
electricity generators and British Coal, which gave the industry a
guaranteed market.
There is concern that the end of the contract will lead to a switch to coal
imports.
