FT  06 FEB 92 / Business site plan for Black Country
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL CHEESERIGHT, Midlands Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Black Country Development Corporation announced plans yesterday to
establish a manufacturing and business focus on a 250-acre site at
Wednesbury, north-east of Birmingham.
The state-funded body, which has the task of regerating one of the UK's most
depressed areas, said it was negotiating with Sandwell Borough Council to
buy the 93 acres of land that were once the Patent Shaft steelworks, which
closed in 1979.
Completion of negotiations, or compulsory acquisition through a
parliamentary vesting order, would complete the assembly of land for the
business area and make the site the largest available for development in the
Black Country.
Mr Michael Heseltine, the environment secretary, has said he would consider
a vesting order, a measure which, after parliamentary debate, permits
transfer of land from one public body to another.
Sandwell has already designated the land at Wednesbury as suitable for
business use. The decision of the development corporation to purchase Patent
Shaft means that plans for a retail and leisure centre have been abandoned.
Speyhawk Land and Estates, the London property group, has outline planning
approval for such a centre, but its plans have been set back by a
combination of financial troubles, the collapse of the commercial property
market and the development of the nearby Merry Hill shopping centre.
