<HEADLINE>
FT  06 FEB 92 / 'Forward looking' US monetary policy urged
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL PROWSE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE US Federal Reserve should be prepared to ease monetary policy further if
the economic recovery expected this spring fails to materialise, Mr Michael
Boskin, the White House chief economic adviser, indicated in a briefing
yesterday.
Releasing the 1992 Economic Report of the president, he said monetary policy
had to be 'forward looking'. He said the Fed had been surprised by the
sluggishness of monetary aggregates in the face of repeated cuts in interest
rates.
In congressional testimony on Tuesday, Mr Alan Greenspan, the Fed chairman,
said he would not rule out further interest rate cuts if the economy failed
to improve. But he hoped the existing stimulus would be sufficient.
The Fed met this week to discuss monetary targets for 1992. Some private
sector economists, including Mr Martin Feldstein, a Harvard professor and
economic adviser in the Reagan White House, have urged the Fed to raise its
monetary target this year. This would probably require further cuts in
interest rates.
Mr Boskin acknowledged that the Bush administration had not yet gained
control of the budget deficit.
There was 'still a huge gaping hole in the budget', he said, referring to
this year's expected shortfall of Dollars 400bn - a record 6.7 per cent of
gross domestic product.
He said the best way to reduce the deficit in the medium-term would be to
restrain growth of spending on entitlement programmes such as health care
for the elderly. This would free resources for private sector investment.
Mr Boskin defended the administration's claim that stimulatory measures in
the budget would raise annual GDP growth 0.4 percentage points in coming
years. He said this reflected 'confidence effects' as well as the incentive
effect of measures such as the proposed cut in capital gains taxes and
temporary investment allowances for companies.
</TEXT>
