<HEADLINE>
FT  05 FEB 92 / Forte cleared over property depreciation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FORTE, the hotels group, yesterday agreed to provide more information on
property depreciation policies in its next annual report, in the fourth
public settlement reached by the Financial Reporting Review Panel, the new
watchdog of the Accounting Standards Board.
The panel said it accepted Forte's explanation and saw no need for further
action, but that the company had agreed to provide more information on
depreciation policies in the future.
The move appeared to clear Forte of any violation of existing accounting
standards, but also implicitly endorsed the practice of not depreciating
certain fixed assets which has been adopted by a significant number of
companies.
Forte does not depreciate freehold properties or leaseholds longer than 20
years, arguing that their long lives and the money spent each year on their
repair and improvement make any depreciation charge 'insignificant'.
The panel investigated the company's approach to see whether it contravened
SSAP 12, an accounting standard that deals with depreciation. It states that
there should be a provision for depreciation on fixed assets with a 'finite
useful economic life' equivalent to the difference between their cost and
their 'estimated residual value'.
In Forte's accounts for the year to January 31 1991, land and buildings held
freehold or on long leases are valued at Pounds 2.7bn or 62 per cent of all
fixed assets, compared with Pounds 2.6bn or 66 per cent for the previous 12
months.
Mr Donald Main, finance director, said the company typically spends about 10
per cent of turnover from its hotels division on improving buildings. That
would represent about Pounds 91m last year.
'Our philosophy is that we invest heavily in our property on a regular basis
to maintain and improve the buildings so they appreciate in value. There is
no logic in depreciating them.'
However, in the absence of any new accounting standard on depreciation, the
panel's acceptance of Forte's accounts is likely to encourage other
companies to continue using similar techniques on their balance sheets.
Mr Allan Cook, technical director of the Accounting Standards Board, said:
'This whole area is in dispute at the moment. We will not dodge the issue
but we want to address it as a whole and not slate individual companies.'
The ASB may issue a draft reporting standard on property values after the
summer.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 19
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT921-10553</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CBEBPAFMFT</PROFILE>
