<HEADLINE>
FT  05 FEB 92 / Jobs: First trial for subsidised self-marketing - Bowater
sponsors advertising space for unemployed business-development executives
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL DIXON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IT takes more than rising with the lark to get one up on a chief executive.
Mind you, the Jobs column thought it had done the trick the other cockcrow
when it telephoned Bowater's David Lyon at his office. 'I'll put you
through,' said a brisk yet friendly operator, and tried . . . but no answer.
So on getting through to him later, I contrived to mention - though
good-humouredly of course - that I had called him before, just after eight.
He knew, he replied. As it was a Monday, he'd had to come in from the
country and had not been at his desk as early as usual. 'But when I got in
and called you back minutes after, you weren't there,' he added. 'You rang
me from home, didn't you?'
Touche ]
The reason for my original dawn activity was that Mr Lyon had let slip the
fact that he is in the habit of conducting job-interviews at 8am, and
candidates who happen to be currently unemployed have impressed him by never
failing to turn up on the dot. But the reason why he made the disclosure in
the first place was the proposal put forward in this corner of the FT a week
ago. As some in today's congregation may not have been present then,
however, I had better recapitulate a little.
The aim of the scheme, brainchild of redundancy victim Peter Laurence, is to
give folk in his unfortunate position a bit of help towards finding new
work. His idea is that this paper should try to provide them with a
subsidised market by inviting employers to contribute - say - half the cost
of a regular space in our recruitment-advertising pages, in which people out
of work could offer their skills at a commensurately reduced price.
When I put the idea to the FT's classified advertisement director Brian
Powell, he not only agreed that it was worth giving a go, but said he'd join
in the sponsoring by running the ad at a special rate. Hence my request last
week for corporate volunteers willing, at least in principle, to support the
enterprise.
The result has been nearly a dozen letters and telephone calls, not all from
enthusiasts for the scheme. Seven, although mostly conceding that it would
do no harm, say it falls far short of what is required. In their view, the
need is for government action, and they suggest various types of taxpayers'
subsidies to persuade organisations to fill their job openings from the
ranks of the unemployed.
To which my own response is that their argument, while perhaps sensible,
misses the point. It may well be that far more help than the sponsored ad is
needed, and that government might get round to providing same in time. But
Mr Laurence's idea has the strength of being something that could be done
quickly, and by a relative handful of companies at that.
Alas, getting the necessary few together is another matter. After all,
companies can be forgiven for not leaping forward to give money at times
like these. Accordingly, I wasn't expecting the idea to become reality for a
while. And nor will it do so - or, at any rate, not in the shape of a
regular sponsored market-place.
But thanks to David Lyon (who for all his difficulties in getting in on time
on Mondays, clearly acts fast) we can run a limited, one-off trial. On his
initiative, Bowater is joining the FT in subsidising an ad big enough to
carry short self-advertisements by six unemployed people with one particular
type of skill - in business development. For those inclined to try selling
themselves therein, however, there are certain snags.
One is that if their message appears, it will cost them Pounds 50. Another
is that they are subject to an absolute top limit of 60 words which must
include their name and any restrictions on where they are willing to work. A
third is that, if the offer is over-subscribed, the six to appear will be
chosen at random. The last is that their copy must reach me here at the
latest on Wednesday, February 19, so the ad can run the following week.
Which said, I'll wait to hear from you.
NOW to the table alongside, which is compiled from the PA Consulting Group's
latest survey of United Kingdom employers' plans for recruiting graduates.
Anyone wanting the survey, price Pounds 420, should contact Jenny Cambridge
of PA at 123 Buckingham Palace Rd, London SW1W 9SR; telephone 071-730 9000,
fax 071-333-5050.
My table is limited to the pay aspects of the 91 participating
organisations' graduate-recruitment policies. The figures, all averages, are
broken down by the employing outfits' sector of activity.
First come the starting salaries actually paid to degree-winners who were
newly taken on in 1991, followed by estimates (where ventured) of those to
be paid to those recruited this year. Then, for the six right-hand columns
of the table, we turn from new entrants to people engaged earlier, and from
basic salaries alone to total cash pay including bonuses.
The first pair of the six refer to graduates with one year's service, the
next two pairs to those with three, and five years respectively. In each
case a distinction is made for quality of work. The first of each pair of
columns shows the typical total cash rewards of just 'adequate' or averagely
performing staff. The second does likewise for their 'high-flying'
counterparts.
From what I hear, demand for new graduates this year is well down even on
the depressed levels of 12 months ago. Nevertheless the estimated starting
salaries are higher, apparently by 14 per cent in the case of banks although
by only 2 per cent on the overall figure.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
