<HEADLINE>
FT  05 FEB 92 / Parliament and Politics: Lamont faces pressure over tax -
Financial Times Poll of Conservative MPs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IF Mr Norman Lamont had any remaining doubts about what he should aim for in
his March 10 Budget, they will have been dispelled by the latest survey of
Conservative opinion at Westminster.
The FT's questionnaire was completed by 107 Tory MPs, representing 30 per
cent of the 367-strong parliamentary party and well over a third of
backbench MPs.
By a margin of more than three to one, government supporters believe the
chancellor should use what the Treasury insists is his strictly limited room
for manoeuvre to reduce income tax rather than to raise public spending.
The 71 per cent in favour of tax cuts compared with 19 per cent who
indicated that they would prefer any boost to the economy to come through
higher public spending. The remaining 10 per cent said that there was not a
direct choice, with most urging Mr Lamont to do both.
The results confirm that the priority of Tory MPs is high-profile action to
demonstrate in the weeks before the general election that the government is
determined to get the economy moving.
Tax cuts are seen as the best way to underline the essential difference
between the Conservatives and Labour during an election campaign which, if
Mr John Major opts for April 9, might start within two days of the Budget
speech.
The MPs appear less sure whether Mr Lamont should opt to raise income tax
thresholds by more than the rate of inflation or cut the basic rate. But the
9-percentage-point majority in favour of the former is significantly smaller
than in previous years, suggesting that a basic-rate reduction would win
strong support from the backbenches.
There is also strong support for measures to boost investment incentives for
industry, with more than 70 per cent of those polled pressing for them. By
contrast, the MPs are relatively evenly divided over whether Mr Lamont
should take special action to help the motor industry or to alleviate the
effects of increases in the uniform business rate.
In spite of the brickbats thrown at the chancellor by sections of media  -
and by some Tory MPs - the survey shows that most in the party are reluctant
to blame him for a recession which remains the main obstacle to a fourth
consecutive election victory.
A handful added disparaging comments about the chancellor to their
questionnaires - 'It would be disloyal to be frank', wrote one. But 60 per
cent rated his performance excellent or good and only 6 per cent
disappointing.
In spite of the constraint it imposes on interest rates, there is general
support for sterling's participation in the exchange rate mechanism of the
European Monetary System. Nearly 30 per cent say it is 'vital' to maintain
the pound's present parity.
There are, however, small minorities on both the right and left of the party
who believe that the ERM is an obstacle to economic recovery. Some 20 per
cent describe the parity as 'unimportant'. A significant proportion of those
said that Mr Lamont should be ready to withdraw sterling from the system.
Overall, Conservative MPs are more equivocal in their commitment to the
present rate against the D-Mark should that threaten a rise in British
interest rates. Only a small majority think Mr Lamont should go as far as a
rise in borrowing costs to defend the pound.
Among other changes sought from the back benches, there are strong
minorities in favour of an extension of tax relief for child care and
reductions in or abolition of inheritance tax, stamp duties and capital
gains taxes.
There are also more eclectic requests. One respondent believes that all
household staff should attract tax relief for their employers, while a
colleague said that Mr Lamont's first priority on March 10 should be
'helping industry to get off its knees'.
Another replied frankly that Mr Lamont's task was to ensure 'the survival of
the government'. But if MPs are worried, few are willing to admit it.
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
            WHAT TORY MPS WOULD LIKE TO SEE IN THE BUDGET
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
Results shown in rounded percentages. The totals do not necessarily add
up to 100 because in some cases the repondents have not answered every
question and in others have chosen more than one option. Questionnaires
were returned by 107 Conservative MPs between January 20 and February 3.
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
 What should Mr Lamont set as his first Budget priority:
  Encouraging economic recovery: 29
  Lower inflation/interest rates: 18
  Help for industry: 9
  Tax cuts: 8
  Winning the election: 5
  Others: 13
