<HEADLINE>
FT  05 FEB 92 / Parliament and Politics: Tories cheered by Nellist's act of
defiance - The impending battle for the Coventry South East constituency
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL CHEESERIGHT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
COVENTRY Conservatives can scarcely believe their luck. Militant Mr Dave
Nellist is to stand as an Independent in South East, a seat they would never
otherwise have expected to win.
The Labour vote is split. Hold the 1987 vote and Martine Hyams, a first-time
candidate, might just squeak in, the Tories argue. And for good measure,
some of the heat might come off Mr John Butcher's marginal seat in
neighbouring South West.
Mr Ken Taylor, the Conservative organiser, said: 'This is the first time we
have had an opportunity of winning this seat.'
Indeed, Mr Nellist in 1983 succeeded Mr William Wilson, who had been a
Coventry Labour MP for 20 years. His critics say that he nearly lost the
seat for Labour in 1983. In 1987, however, Mr Nellist pushed his majority up
to a comfortable 17.6 per cent, or 6,653 votes.
Coventry South East is not a natural Conservative seat, especially not in a
recession. Although the proportion of home ownership is high, there are
extensive council estates and rundown areas with, in one ward, a high ethnic
population. Unemployment, in a population largely of skilled workers, has
been rising.
The Conservative campaign will be energetic but discreet. Mrs Hyams will
avoid direct confrontation with Mr Nellist. She will be a standard
Conservative. The aim will be to get the vote out - greater than the total
of more than 11,000 last time. The real struggle of the campaign will be for
the Labour vote. The conundrum is calculating the portion that will remain
loyal to Mr Nellist.
Now the outcast, Mr Nellist maintains that it is not he who has lost the way
but the Labour party itself. To the extent that he will address the broad
issues, it will be from a 1970s and early 1980s hard-left viewpoint 'in
defence of the socialist ideas the Labour Party was built on'. That means
unashamedly arguing for defence cuts, socialist planning and democracy, he
said.
Only he can keep the Conservatives out, he argues, not, as he puts it,
'somebody imposed from the outside.'
He grants that the record of independents in general elections is not
encouraging, but is quick to add: 'The historical trend can be bucked.'
Such arguments drive orthodox Labour supporters to apoplexy. It is not only
that the electorate has spent the last decade voting against hard-left
political solutions. It is not only because they believe he has frightened
Labour supporters away. It is also that they feel he identifies with
trouble.
Mr Duncan Simpson, divisional organiser of the Amalgamated Engineering Union
snorted: 'If anything, he thrives on stress. A good MP seeks to avoid it
happening.'
Mr Simpson added: 'We need an MP who is going to help Coventry regain its
manufacturing profile.' Coventry is the centre of the motor industry, the
argument runs, and yet investors like the Japanese go elsewhere.
For the next week or two, until an official Labour candidate emerges, Mr
Nellist has the field to himself.
By operating a more democratic selection procedure, Labour is seeking to
destroy the accusation that its candidate will be imposed.
Nomination papers went out last Monday. A shortlist will be drawn up by the
Labour national executive committee and there will then be a postal vote
among local party members to select a candidate. So far, there is no obvious
choice, certainly nobody with the local profile of Mr Nellist.
Meanwhile, Nellist supporters are out and about, canvassing. They claim
promises of support from 33.4 per cent of 13,400 people interviewed.
Mr Nellist said he was 'on target to win the seat'. He agreed, however, that
the returns needed to be treated with some caution because they tended to
understate the number of abstentions.
The Conservatives think returns need to be treated with caution because the
sort of people doing the canvassing are not the sort of people to whom you
would want to say 'no'.
General Election 1987: DJ Nellist (Lab), 17,969; A. Grant (C), 11,316; F.
Devine (SDP/All), 8,095; N. Hutchinson (Grn), 479. Lab Majority 6,653.
</TEXT>
