FT  05 FEB 92 / Parliament and Politics: Lib Dem plan for housing - News in
Brief
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
MORTGAGE interest tax relief should be phased out and replaced with a new
housing cost allowance, targeted at the lower paid, and covering both rents
and mortgages, the Liberal Democrats said yesterday.
The party's 'Manifesto for Housing' said mortgage tax relief had created
'enormous economic and social problems without actually being of benefit to
home owners'.
Tax relief would continue to be available for existing mortgage holders.
For those entering the housing market, relief would be available at a level
equivalent to a proportion of housing costs - perhaps 50 per cent - between
regionally-determined lower and upper limits.
*****
DEFENCE: Mr Tom King, defence secretary, told the Commons yesterday that the
final cost of the Trident nuclear missile submarine programme was now
estimated to be Pounds 10.518bn.
He said: 'This marks a further small reduction against last year's estimate
and an overall real reduction of Pounds 3bn against the 1982 forecast'.
He confirmed that the order for the fourth submarine at VSEL Barrow would be
placed as soon as contract talks were completed.
*****
ENVIRONMENT: Mr John Major is to host a Downing Street seminar today on the
environment, attended by representatives of 'green' lobby groups and
industrialists. Officials said the prime minister was preparing for the
United Nations conference on environment and development which he hopes to
attend in Rio de Janeiro in June.
