FT  05 FEB 92 / Parliament and Politics: Pledge on size of classes - Labour
Education Policy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A COMMITMENT to ensure that there are no classes of more than 40 pupils
within the first year of a Labour government was made in an opposition
offensive on education yesterday.
Mr Jack Straw, shadow education secretary, said that the pledge would cost
about Pounds 3m and would affect between 9,000 and 10,000 children. The
money could be found from existing plans for education spending.
Mr Neil Kinnock, the Labour leader, said that a continuation of Tory
policies would mean 'more of the same back-of-the-envelope chopping and
changing, and a persistently undervalued and under-invested state system'.
The move, which is the second initiative on education in as many days, forms
part of Labour's effort to turn the political debate to public-service
issues, traditionally its stronger ground.
Labour's attack on the increase in class sizes under the Tories was directed
particularly at the rise in the number of classes with more than 30 pupils.
Mr Straw said that while Labour would embark on a programme of year-by-year
reductions in maximum class sizes, with the hope of reaching a maximum of 35
by the end of the third year, he could give no target date for making 30
children the class limit.
Mr Kinnock ridiculed the remarks made at the weekend by Mr Kenneth Clarke,
the education secretary, that he had 'no objection' to the re-emergence of
grammar schools, saying that Mr Clarke was 'succumbing to nostalgia for the
1950s'.
Labour repeated its broad promise to reverse the drop in the percentage of
national wealth spent on education, but Mr Clarke said that the opposition
had 'clearly abandoned their recent pledge to spend an extra Pounds 2.6bn on
education'.
</TEXT>
