FT  05 FEB 92 / Parliament and Politics: Heseltine optimistic over poll tax
levels - Local Government
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH and PHILIP STEPHENS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE government set its face against Budget changes to the poll tax system
yesterday, as Mr Michael Heseltine, the environment secretary, expressed
optimism about the size of bills for the coming year. Ministers also
resisted renewed pressure to help businesses facing large increases in the
business rate.
Mr Michael Portillo, local-government minister, said the Department of the
Environment had neither sought nor expected Budget changes to the uniform
business rate, in spite of representations from organisations such as the
Confederation of British Industry. Industry has been pressing for improved
transitional relief.
Mr Heseltine said in the Commons that Labour's 'gloomy predictions' that
poll tax bills would be nearer Pounds 300 than the government's target of
Pounds 257 would not be fulfilled.
During a debate on government grants to councils, he told MPs that in the
third quarter of the current financial year, 29 per cent of the budgeted
yield had been collected, compared with 28 per cent in the third quarter of
the previous year. The total budgeted yield collected in the first nine
months of the year is, however, down on that for the previous year, at 68
per cent and 74 per cent respectively.
Earlier, Mr Portillo told a Westminster press conference that the losers
under the business revaluation - concentrated in the south-east  - would be
balanced by the large number of gainers from the revaluation in areas such
as the north of England.
The Institute for Fiscal Studies estimates that the phasing in of property
revaluation that coincided with the abolition of domestic rates three years
ago will mean increases of 20 per cent plus inflation for 390,000 businesses
in the next financial year.
The CBI is among many business groups that have called for the increases to
be suspended because of the financial pressures imposed on industry by the
recession.
During the debate, ministers offered little comfort in the face of
cross-party backbench protests about how the government distributed grant
among councils and decided how much they needed to spend - their standard
spending assessments.
Mr John Biffen, a former Tory cabinet minister, warned that while Shropshire
county council had staved off cuts in nursery education by drawing on
balances, that route offered no longer-term solution.
Mr Bryan Gould, shadow environment secretary, accused Mr Heseltine of
manipulating the grant system to benefit Tory shire districts.
</TEXT>
