<HEADLINE>
FT  05 FEB 92 / UK News (Employment): EC job opportunities surveyed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CATHERINE MILTON, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MANAGERS and technical staff will be the categories of people with most
opportunities to work in other European countries next year, according to a
survey of more than 200 Scottish employers.
The research, part of a project on the implications of the single European
market for vocational education and training, found that 40 per cent of
staff recruited from other EC countries filled either management or
technical posts.
The report, to be published shortly in the Industrial Relations Journal,
found that 50 per cent of employers surveyed believed the completion of the
single market next year would make no difference to recruitment and that
they were satisfied with local labour.
A substantial minority, 45 per cent, believed recruitment would be affected.
That view is widely held by larger companies, those with more than 100
employees. Researchers say larger companies are likely to have a better
understanding of the European labour market.
A third of companies had employed staff from other EC countries. The largest
companies (those with more than 500 employees) and those with EC links are
most likely to recruit staff from other EC countries.
Expanding business with the country concerned was cited by 20 per cent of
employers as the reason for recruiting staff from other EC countries.
More than 50 per cent of companies in service industries expected to recruit
staff from other EC countries, compared with 40 per cent in manufacturing
and construction.
The Single European Market and Labour Mobility, Industrial Relations
Journal, Volume 23, No 2, Spring 1992. Blackwell, 108 Cowley Road, Oxford,
OX4 1JF. By subscription.
</TEXT>
