FT  05 FEB 92 / More debt centre cash urged from societies
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BARCHARD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BUILDING societies were asked yesterday by Mr Edward Leigh, consumer affairs
minister, to provide more cash for money advice centres to help people with
debt difficulties.
Mr Leigh met six of the largest societies on Monday together with
representatives of the Money Advice Trust in an attempt to improve
co-operation between societies and the trust, which was set up to raise
money for debt counselling.
Building societies have been criticised for being less generous in
contributing to money advice centres than banks and other lenders, even
though many building society customers have suffered severely with debts.
The largest donation to the trust by a building society has come from
Nationwide, the second-biggest society. It announced last week that it was
giving Pounds 345,000 to fund a money advice support unit in London.
Mr Leigh said yesterday that although obtaining money advice funding from
societies had been slower than expected, he was hopeful about progress.
