<HEADLINE>
FT  05 FEB 92 / Number of estate agency branches shows steep drop
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BARCHARD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE ESTATE agency industry in Britain has contracted sharply because of the
housing market recession, a survey has found.
The total number of estate agency branches has fallen from a peak of 6,500
in 1988 to just over 5,000 at the end of last year, according to the
February edition of Estate Agency News, a trade magazine.
Only two agency chains, Royal Life and Halifax, now have more than 500
branches each, compared with seven chains in 1988. At that time, Royal Life
and Halifax had more than 800 branches each and were trying to reach a
target of 1,000 branches.
Most of the large chains are continuing to make heavy losses, and the
magazine describes the estate agency business as an industry in decline.
Prudential Property Services, then the largest agency in the market, has
since withdrawn altogether, shutting down 250 branches and selling more than
600.
However, some chains are still growing, usually by buying the branches of
the longer-established loss-making chains such as Prudential Property
Services.
One of the most impressive new entrants to the market is Woolwich Building
Society, which bought 210 offices from Prudential and re-established the
Chesterton brand name in central London. Woolwich, which had no chain at the
height of the housing boom, now has 400 offices - putting it ahead of
Nationwide, the second-largest building society, which has fallen back to
378 agencies from 400.
Connell, owned by Scottish Widows, the life assurance company, has added 68
branches, also bought from Prudential Property Services. A further 30
branches purchased from Prudential by Connell were closed.
A new chain, Arun Estates, has been set up to take over 108 branches from
Prudential. It is now the largest privately owned chain in the UK.
Altogether the top 20 agencies closed one in 10 of their branches last year,
and the contraction of the industry looks likely to continue for the
foreseeable future.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
