<HEADLINE>
FT  05 FEB 92 / Sales of houses 'fell by 7% to 1.24m last year'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR, Construction Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE NUMBER of house sales in Britain fell 7 per cent to 1.24m last year,
compared with 1.34m in 1990, according to figures published yesterday by
James R. Adams, the independent research consultancy.
Transactions last year were 40 per cent fewer than in 1988, when the housing
market was at its peak.
The figures underline the depth of the recession in the market, which in the
past few weeks has seen renewed interest from prospective house purchasers.
The consultancy said sales in an average year would be about 1.5m, or 20 per
cent higher than in 1990 and last year.
The figures were calculated from a sample of 12,500 transactions involving
more than 20,500 individuals and submitted by a panel of more than 100
solicitors. They showed that house sales dipped sharply in October, November
and December after rallying in the previous three months.
Mr Jimmy Adams, chairman of the consultancy, said: 'It takes several months
to complete sales after purchasers have agreed to buy. It is therefore
likely to be early summer before we can be sure whether the current upsurge
in interest has resulted in higher sales.
'The rally which took place last autumn probably reflected increased
confidence following the end of the Gulf war,' he continued.
'This evaporated as people became more concerned about job prospects and the
state of the economy.'
According to the consultancy, sales fell 10 per cent to 301,581 in the final
three months of last year compared with the previous three months. Sales
were 12 per cent lower than in the final three months of 1990.
The cash value of sales last year was Pounds 77.27bn compared with Pounds
80.08bn in 1990 and Pounds 114.92bn in 1988. The percentage of properties
bought for cash has fallen from 19.1 per cent in 1988 to 14.2 per cent last
year. Loans accounted for 71.3 per cent of purchases last year compared with
66.8 per cent four years ago.
People moving to another region accounted for 17 per cent of house sales
last year. The largest group moving between regions was from greater London
to south-east England. The second-largest was those moving from the
south-east to the south-west.
The survey also showed that nearly three quarters of those moving paid more
for their new home than they had for their old one, in spite of lower prices
in London, southern England and in the Yorkshire area, said the consultancy.
Most builders and estate agents expect the number of house sales to increase
this year as buyers who have been staying out of the market take advantage
of lower prices. Few, however, expect prices to increase this year.
A survey of 27 house builders conducted by stockbrokers Barclay de Zoete
Wedd found that nearly two thirds of the companies had seen an increase in
activity since the new year. Seventy per cent of the builders expected sales
to increase this year, while 67 per cent said house prices were unlikely to
increase even if sales rose.
BZW said it expected a gentle upturn in the market this year.
The Adams Residential Property Index - 1991. James R. Adams Associates, 5
Langley Street, London WC2H 9JA. Pounds 2,100.
</TEXT>
