<HEADLINE>
FT  05 FEB 92 / World Trade News: Lauda Air may choose GE engines
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL BETTS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LAUDA AIR, the Austrian airline owned by Mr Niki Lauda, is expected to
announce this week it has chosen US General Electric GE90 engines to power
its new Boeing 777 widebody aircraft instead of the Rolls-Royce Trent and
the Pratt &amp; Whitney PW4000, Paul Betts writes.
The deal is expected to be worth over Dollars 150m (Pounds 82m). Lauda Air
is the second airline after British Airways to opt for the new GE90 heavy
thrust engine for its new Boeing 777 fleet. The Austrian airline placed
orders last year for four Boeing 777s, with delivery between 1997 and 2000.
The three leading aero-engine makers are in fierce competition to win
customers for their new heavy thrust engines to power the new Boeing 777s.
The market for large engines is expected to account for an increasingly
important share of the commercial engine business over the next 10 years as
airlines expand their widebody fleets.
With the Lauda Air order going to GE, the field has levelled out, with
Rolls-Royce placing its Trent engine with two Boeing 777 customers (Thai
International and Emirates), and Pratt &amp; Whitney winning Boeing 777 engine
orders with United Airlines and All Nippon Airways.
</TEXT>
