<HEADLINE>
FT  05 FEB 92 / Most Tory MPs want tax cuts in Budget
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AN overwhelming majority of Conservative MPs wants Mr Norman Lamont to give
priority to tax cuts in any pre-election boost to the economy in his Budget
on March 10.
An FT survey of opinion among the government's supporters at Westminster
shows that those favouring tax cuts outnumber by more than three to one
those who would prefer a stimulus to come from higher public spending.
The results - gathered from detailed questionnaires returned by 107, or
nearly a third, of Conservative MPs - come amid widespread acknowledgement
in Whitehall that the economy's emergence from recession has been further
delayed.
Senior officials acknowledged yesterday that the Treasury was revising down
its growth forecasts in the approach to the Budget as the recession provoked
another fierce House of Commons row between Mr John Major and Mr Neil
Kinnock.
Mr Kinnock accused Mr Major of being responsible for the longest recession
since the 1930s, while the prime minister hit back by accusing the Labour
leader of 'economic illiteracy'.
The officials acknowledged that slower growth would mean a higher public
sector borrowing requirement, but said it would also strengthen the case for
use of the 'fiscal stabilisers' which would allow a higher budget deficit.
That is the traditional Whitehall code to indicate there should still be
room for tax cuts.
The FT poll coincides with an intense debate among senior ministers on
whether the chancellor should make a cut from 25p to 24p in the basic rate
of income tax the centrepiece of next month's Budget. The growing number in
favour argue that since Labour is pledged to reverse such a reduction it
would provide the Conservatives an ideal platform for an April 9 election.
That argument will be strengthened by the majority of backbench MPs shown by
the survey to view lower income taxes as essential to secure the
government's re-election. Some 71 per cent of the MPs said they would prefer
income tax cuts over any increase in public spending. Last night the
backbenchers were putting that view to Mr Lamont and his Treasury team at a
Westminster meeting.
Of those saying tax cuts should be the priority, a small majority - 52 per
cent against 43 per cent - said they would prefer an increase in the
thresholds at which people begin to pay tax rather than a lower basic rate.
But that difference is small enough to ensure that whichever course Mr
Lamont adopted would win the strong backing of the Tory party at
Westminster.
A majority of respondents to the survey also want the chancellor to
introduce measures to increase investment.
In addition, there are strong lobbies urging the chancellor to boost their
chances in the election by extending tax relief for working mothers and by
announcing reductions in inheritance and capital gains taxes.
The survey shows that more than 60 per cent rate Mr Lamont's performance as
excellent or good.
Poll details, Page 10
