<HEADLINE>
FT  05 FEB 92 / Labour considers redefining PSBR
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN and DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Labour party is consid-ering redefining the public sector borrowing
requirement (PSBR) to exclude funds raised for some types of investment in
transport and housing.
The party is also exploring ways of improving public bodies' access to
private funding, including making it easier for local authorities to raise
finance directly from the capital markets.
The aim would be to allow an incoming Labour government to increase spending
on transport and housing without raising the PSBR, a key indicator of
government economic performance.
The Tories immediately accused the opposition of intending to 'cook the
books', and called the plan the latest Labour economic fiasco.
Mr Chris Patten, the Tory party chairman, said: 'Yet again Labour's economic
policy has been seen to be full of holes . . . Labour would employ the
Arthur Daley approach to book-keeping.'
Labour's two-pronged approach may eventually have broader applications. One
senior Labour politician suggested yesterday that access to joint public and
private financing could be granted more freely without undermining the
prudential approach to public spending that the party is seeking to convey.
The party denied any link between its spending plans and proposals to make
the UK's public accounts more transparent, saying the two had 'no connection
whatsoever'.
Labour Treasury frontbenchers insist that the only new expenditure which
will be sanctioned immediately after an election would be on child benefit
and state pensions. But the party is keen to find ways of increasing
investment in public services which would not count as public expenditure in
many other European Community countries.
One potential source of finance would be local authorities' Pounds 8bn of
capital receipts from council house sales. Mr Clive Soley, Labour's housing
spokesman, repeated yesterday, during a debate organised by Roof magazine,
the party's promise to release more of these funds for housing.
Challenged by Sir George Young, housing minister, on whether this would
count as additional public expenditure, Mr Soley said the definition of
public sector borrowing would be changed to exclude certain types of
expenditure - including recycling of capital receipts into housing
investment.
Mr Soley was at pains to stress that Labour merely intended to bring
'restrictive' public accounts conventions in the UK broadly into line with
European practice.
Labour later disowned his remarks, saying Mr Soley had been wrong to suggest
that PSBR definitions would be changed to accommodate the release of capital
receipts.
The EC is expected to develop standard measures of performance - including
for government borrowing - under the rules for governing economic
convergence in the treaty for economic and monetary union.
Labour is also considering separating current spending from capital
investment in a further reform of traditional public accounts conventions.
Both forms of expenditure are currently lumped together within the PSBR.
On the spending side, Labour is contemplating extending the right of local
authorities to raise long-term finance by issuing municipal bonds. The party
stresses, however, that bonds would only be used to provide local authority
financing 'at the margin'.
Education pledge, Page 10
</TEXT>
