<HEADLINE>
FT  05 FEB 92 / Car sales freedom recommended: Monopolies report may result
in cheaper cars by extending choice for dealers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GRIFFITHS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CARS could be made cheaper in the UK by giving dealers more freedom to
choose which makes of car to sell and how to sell them, according to a
Monopolies and Mergers Commission report to be published today.
But the long-awaited, 1,000-page report is likely to disappoint consumer
groups in giving only partial support to their persistent claims that car
prices overall in the UK are excessively high compared with the main EC
markets.
While accepting that private motorists are confused by UK pricing
structures, the report concludes that neither manufacturers nor their
distributors are guilty of price fixing or systematic profiteering. It also
concludes that the existing system of selling cars through exclusively
franchised dealers does not necessarily work to consumers' disadvantage.
It was to investigate these twin issues that the MMC report was first
commissioned two years ago.
It is understood largely to accept the arguments of the industry that the
franchised dealer system, with its dedicated service and repair facilities
and other after-sales support, is a beneficial way of dealing with complex
products with major safety implications.
In this respect the report is likely to be regarded as a partial 'whitewash'
by consumer groups critical of the retail motor trade's performance.
The report concentrates on freeing up areas of competition within the
industry's existing structure. If adopted they should help substantially to
increase marketplace competition. The five key recommendations are
understood to be:
Removal of restrictions on dealers advertising outside their
manufacturer-designated sales territories;
Ending of manufacturer-imposed restrictions on the number of outlets selling
their models that any one retailing group may own. Ford, the UK market
leader, limits it to eight, for example. The issue is important because some
manufacturers have become concerned at the bargaining power which can be
exerted by the large public groups which are increasingly involving
themselves in the motor trade;
An end to manufacturer restrictions on dealer groups owning rival franchises
within their designated sales territories, although the MMC does not go so
far as to say that multi-franchising should be allowed on a single site;
An end to restrictions on dealers setting up parts sales or fast-fit
operations within the franchised territories;
The forced removal of unit sales ceilings that some manufacturers impose on
individual dealers.
The industry's initial reactions to the report appeared to be that, while it
had not been given a wholly clean bill of health, the MMC's decision not to
recommend abolition of exclusive franchises or other fundamental changes had
exonerated the industry from the worst charges made against it.
While the detailed conclusions on price levels will not be known until later
today, they are expected to show a varied picture, in which private
motorists fare relatively badly compared with the fleet and other business
purchasers who account for more than half of the total UK new car sales.
Nissan dispute, Page 8
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 1
</PAGE>
