<HEADLINE>
FT  05 FEB 92 / Granada pledges to honour commitment to quality TV
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GRANADA GROUP gave a written commitment to the Independent Television
Commission last week that Granada Television would honour the terms of its
licence in spite of the forced resignation of Mr David Plowright as
executive chairman.
The pledge by Mr Alex Bernstein, chairman of the parent company, was
submitted in case Granada's undertakings on programme quality in its
successful application for a new 10-year licence were called into question.
Mr Plowright was told on January 27 by Mr Gerry Robinson, Granada's new
group chief executive, he would have to resign. His effective dismissal was
announced on Monday.
Mr George Russell, ITC chairman, signalled the commission's concern over the
licence terms last week when he warned that the decision to remove Mr
Plowright was a mistake that could perhaps have serious commercial
implications for Granada.
The remark was made, it is believed, at a private meeting held at the ITC
between Mr Russell, Mr Plowright and Mr Andrew Quinn, who becomes chief
executive of Granada TV after Mr Plowright leaves at the end of this month.
Mr Plowright had led Granada's successful application for a new licence in
spite of being heavily outbid by Mr Phil Redmond's Northwest Television.
He is one of the most respected figures in British commercial television and
has worked for Granada for more than 30 years.
He was so devastated when told he would have to resign that he asked Mr
Quinn, who was not involved in the decision, to take over the post
immediately. Mr Quinn, who has worked at Granada for the past 27 years,
argued that the ITC had to be informed and a meeting with Mr Russell took
place on Thursday.
The ITC was clearly shocked by the move to oust Mr Plowright so soon after
the company was given its new licence. In spite of the ITC's misgivings, his
removal was accepted on the grounds that a broadcasting licence was awarded
to a management team and not to an individual.
The ITC last night declined to comment on what had been discussed.
On Monday, senior programme executives at Granada said that the peremptory
removal of their chairman had 'undermined the confidence of the senior
programme management in the intentions of Granada Group to honour the
licence commitments required by the ITC'.
Mr Bernstein, clearly irritated that Mr Plowright's removal was being
interpreted as a case of 'profits before quality', said yesterday: 'I am
surprised that people assume we are going to stop making quality television
and stop making a major contribution to the ITV network. We will continue to
do both.'
Little-known group makes top bid for national radio channel, Page 8
