<TEXT>
MITSUI Engineering and Shipbuilding, the leading Japanese shipbuilder and
part of the Mitsui group, plans to double capital spending in its
shipbuilding business to Y6bn (Dollars 47.5m) in fiscal 1992, Kyodo reports
from Tokyo.
It initially planned to invest Y10bn in plant and shipbuilding equipment
during a five-year period beginning in fiscal year 1989.
The shipbuilding business has since come out of a slump, and with many new
orders on its books, Mitsui Engineering has decided to boost investment in
1992.
The company plans to improve the efficiency of its shipbuilding operations
by spending about Y2bn to modernise a painting plant.
The improvements are aimed at expanding the facility's capacity, allowing
construction of more double-hull tankers, which are in greater demand due to
increasing concerns about marine pollution from oil spills.
