FT  05 FEB 92 / Observer: Wise men
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
It's good to hear that Lord Shawcross - 90 yesterday - still regularly turns
up for work at J P Morgan's London branch where he advises on international
matters. He is one of a select group of wise old birds including Warburg's
Henry Grunfeld (87) and Lord Roll (84), who do a daily stint at their city
desks. Hermann Abs (90) also checks in occasionally at Deutsche Bank.
Recent events at conglomerates like Hanson and Lonrho have highlighted
understandable institutional concerns about who is going to succeed some of
Britain's ageing captains of industry. Indeed, some big pension funds like
Postel now have a policy of opposing the re-election of any director who is
70 or over. However, this seems far too mechanistic, especially since some
of the world's best-run financial institutions feel the need to listen to
their elder statesmen.
Indeed, Observer hears that National Bank of Kuwait has a director - Khaled
Al-Hamad - who is in his 110th year. . . .
