FT  05 FEB 92 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Amsterdam is an unusually photogenic city and Barry Foster an actor who
occasionally turns in an impressive performance, yet Van der Valk has never
been one of my favourite detective series. Still, the new two-hour episodes
produced by ITV may prove as successful as those great slabs of 'Inspector
Morse' in ratings terms. Today's story is about South American drug dealers,
money laundering, diamonds - pretty much what you expect (8.00).
As a conscientious objector in a non-combatant job my father taught PT. In
my schooldays we did gym. When my children were at school they did PE. Now,
it seems, more and more children do no form of exercise at school. Told that
regular exercise is a key factor in building a healthy heart and that the
seeds of heart disease are sown in childhood, Dispatches discovers that only
five per cent of boys and even fewer girls are doing enough exercise to
develop healthy hearts (9.00 C4).
The final part of BBC1's biography, Churchill (9.30), covers the last 20
years from the end of the war until the death of the old warhorse in 1965,
including his failure to win the 1945 election and his success in 1951 at
the age of 76.
