<HEADLINE>
FT  05 FEB 92 / Protest at pollution curbs delay
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN HUNT, Environment Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A PROTEST about delays in granting licences to National Power and PowerGen
to operate under the Environmental Protection Act was sent to Mr Michael
Heseltine, environment secretary, by Friends of the Earth yesterday.
The two companies should have been given authorisations by the Pollution
Inspectorate by the end of August. They would put limits on power-station
emissions.
The act requires details of the companies' applications to be placed on a
public register. The companies appealed against that on grounds of
commercial confidentiality.
The Department of the Environment yesterday said a report on the appeals had
been written and was with Mr Heseltine.
FoE said because of the delay the companies had been operating without
authorisation for nearly five months.
The environmental group leaked a letter from National Power to the Pollution
Inspectorate in which the company said it was concerned that the information
in its application 'will enable competitors and suppliers to analyse and
assess National Power's operating regime and calculate the effect on
National Power's costs.'
It said: 'We must protect National Power's commercial position against both
potential competitors and suppliers.'
Ms Fiona Weir, FoE air pollution campaigner, said Mr Heseltine was allowing
the power generators to hold up implementation of 'vital new pollution laws'
as they applied to power stations.
</TEXT>
