<DOCNO>FT921-10746</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CBFBFAAFFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920205
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  05 FEB 92 / International Company News: Control Data in red after
charges
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LOUISE KEHOE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SAN FRANCISCO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
CONTROL Data, the US computer systems and services company, suffered a net
loss for 1991 after restructuring charges. Revenues declined as sales of
computer products and automated lottery equipment slowed, the company said.
Net losses for the year were Dollars 9.8m, or 24 cents a share, on revenues
of Dollars 1.5bn. In 1990, Control Data reported net earnings of Dollars
2.7m, or 5 cents, on revenues of Dollars 1.7bn. Excluding pre-tax
restructuring charges of Dollars 12.1m, the company was modestly profitable
for the year.
It reported a fourth-quarter net loss of Dollars 15.2m, or 36 cents, after a
restructuring charge of Dollars 17.5m as the company realigned its computer
products operations. Last year, it suffered a net loss of Dollars 23.8m, or
56 cents.
Revenues for the fourth quarter declined to Dollars 402.9m from Dollars
429.7m.
'Satisfactory results in most of the information services businesses and
government systems were more than offset by the effect that the
deteriorating economy and industry issues had on the automated wagering and
computer products businesses, and by restructuring charges,' said Mr
Lawrence Perlman, president and chief executive.
Restructuring plans, announced last September, have reduced costs and
expenses, the company said.
</TEXT>
