<HEADLINE>
FT  04 FEB 92 / World Stock Markets (America): Pharmaceuticals feature as
Dow trades quietly
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KAREN ZAGOR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
A QUIET day on Wall Street saw US equities trading in a narrow range as
investors waited for details of the Treasury's refunding next week, writes
Karen Zagor in New York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average stood 10.73 higher at 3,234.12 on
unexceptional volume of 182.1m shares. Advancing issues had a very slim edge
on those declining.
Among broader market indices, the Standard &amp; Poor's 500 was 0.74 higher to
close at 409.53. On Friday, the Dow closed 21.47 lower at 3,223.39.
There was little reaction to the release of the purchasing managers report
for January or to a decline in US construction spending in December, both of
which painted a picture of a contracting economy.
Drug companies dominated big board trading. Glaxo eased Dollars  1/4 to
Dollars 30 1/2 , Bristol-Myers Squibb held steady at Dollars 79 7/8 and
Upjohn added Dollars 1 3/4 to Dollars 43 on the back of a positive analysts'
comments about preliminary studies of the company's lazaroid drug.
Digital Equipment advanced Dollars 1 3/4 to Dollars 52 1/8 after Merrill
Lynch highlighted the buying opportunity of the stock and raised its rating.
Ashland Coal rose Dollars 3 to Dollars 31 1/4 after the company said it
would buy Dal-Tex Coal for Dollars 250m. Up to Dollars 50m can be paid in
stock.
Food and tobacco giant RJR Nabisco was one of the most heavily-traded issues
on the New York Stock Exchange, adding Dollars  1/8 to Dollars 10 3/8 . The
company turned in fourth quarter net earnings of Dollars 368m or 22 cents a
share compared with a net loss of Dollars 429m or Dollars 1.11 a year
earlier.
Safeway edged Dollars  5/8 lower to Dollars 18 after turning in
disappointing fourth quarter results. Among actively-traded blue chip
issues, IBM advanced Dollars 1 3/8 to Dollars 91 3/8 , Mobil added Dollars
1/4 to Dollars 64 1/8 and Pepsico lost Dollars  1/4 to Dollars 33 1/2 .
Dow Chemical edged Dollars  1/8 lower to Dollars 54 1/8 while Corning
advanced Dollars  7/8 to Dollars 63 7/8 after Dow Corning, a 50-50 joint
venture, turned in fourth quarter earnings of Dollars 28.9m including a
Dollars 25m pre-tax charge for costs associated with the company's silicone
breast implants.
US Biosciences was one of the biggest losers of the day on the American
Stock Exchange, plunging Dollars 13 1/2 to Dollars 17 3/4 after its ethyol
drug for use in chemotherapy failed to get Food &amp; Drug Administration
approval.
In the secondary market, the Nasdaq composite rose 3.22 to 623.43 in late
trading. Alliance Pharmaceutical was one of the most active over-the-counter
stocks, jumping Dollars 5 3/4 to Dollars 35 3/4 following favourable
comments on the stock on a television programme.
Microsoft climbed Dollars 4 3/4 to Dollars 125 on news of a corporate
restructuring. Among other active over-the-counter issues, Apple Computer
rose Dollars 1 to Dollars 65 3/4 and Intel eased Dollars  1/8 to Dollars 59
3/4 .
Advanced Interventional jumped Dollars 2 to Dollars 19. The stock was halted
on Friday ahead of news that the FDA had approved its angioplasty laser
system.
Canada
TORONTO ended a lacklustre session showing little change. The TSE-300 was
down 1.72 to 3594.40. Declines led advances by 291 to 269. At 24.9m shares,
volume was similar to Friday's 24.7m, while trading value was CDollars
272.7m, up from CDollars 296.7m.
Canadian Pacific, which announced a fourth quarter loss of CDollars 887.6m,
closed up CDollars  1/8 , at CDollars 18 1/8 .
Renaissance Energy fell CDollars  1/8 to CDollars 13 1/4 after reporting
lower fourth-quarter and full-year earnings.
</TEXT>
