<HEADLINE>
FT  04 FEB 92 / International Company News: BCE moves on Teleglobe
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GIBBENS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MONTREAL
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
CANADA'S telecommunications company, BCE, is near its goal of winning
control of Teleglobe, the overseas telephone and data monopoly.
BCE cannot, by law, own more than one-third of Teleglobe, a regulated
utility. It now has four directors in Teleglobe's boardroom, and for two
years has tried to arrange alliances with other large shareholders to oust
Teleglobe's management.
It fears Teleglobe in non-friendly hands could divert heavy overseas voice
and data traffic to competitive systems, including US companies.
BCE owns the largest telecommunications utility, Bell Canada, and, with
several other telephone companies, effectively runs the domestic system.
The battle came to a head yesterday at a Teleglobe board meeting. Following
an alliance with directors representing other big Teleglobe share-holders,
BCE succeeded in getting Mr Charles Sirois appointed Teleglobe chief
executive. He is thought to be friendly to BCE.
Mr Sirois will head a president's office at Teleglobe, and a new board of
directors will be proposed at Teleglobe's annual meeting this spring.
</TEXT>
