<HEADLINE>
FT  04 FEB 92 / International Company News: LTV to sell defence side to
Lockheed and Marietta
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
LTV, the steel group which has been in Chapter 11 bankruptcy since 1986, has
agreed in principle to sell its aircraft and missiles businesses to a
newly-formed company jointly owned by defence contractors Lockheed and
Martin Marietta.
LTV put its defence businesses up for auction in May last year as part of
its plan to reorganise its finances and emerge from bankruptcy.
A joint venture bid by rival aerospace companies is unusual and some
analysts argue it could form a precedent others could follow as the US
defence industry enters a period of consolidation.
The terms of the agreement were not disclosed, but the joint venture is
believed to have offered over Dollars 350m for the business, which employs
16,000 people and has sales of Dollars 2bn. Other companies believed to have
been interested in all or parts of the group include Thomson of France.
The deal is still subject to bankruptcy court approval and it is possible
rival bidders could put in a fresh offer. The LTV business makes missiles
for the Pentagon's strategic defence initiative and is also involved in the
fabrication of large parts for the C-17 military transport and Boeing
civilian aircraft.
Lockheed yesterday reported fourth-quarter net earnings of Dollars 103m, or
Dollars 1.63 a share, up 4 per cent from the Dollars 99m, or Dollars 1.57,
in the same period of 1990. Sales dipped 7 per cent to Dollars 2.7bn.
Operating profits from the missiles and space sector dipped from Dollars
110m to Dollars 88m, while technological services fell from Dollars 15m to
Dollars 9m and electronic systems from Dollars 15m to Dollars 13. But
aeronautical systems profits rose from Dollars 41m to Dollars 75m.
Full-year net earnings were Dollars 308m, or Dollars 4.86 a share, on sales
of Dollars 9.8bn, compared with Dollars 335m, or Dollars 5.30, on sales of
Dollars 9.9bn. Mr Dan Tellep, chairman, noted that non-Department of Defence
revenues rose from 26 to 30 per cent of the total and he expected this trend
to continue.
</TEXT>
