<HEADLINE>
FT  04 FEB 92 / UK Company News: Union Intl nears deal on 3-year funding
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHIYO NAKAMOTO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
UNION INTERNATIONAL, the financially troubled trading arm of the Vestey
Group, one of the UK's largest private companies, said it has reached
agreement in principle with its bankers on the terms of a three-year funding
facility.
Union, which includes the Dewhurst butchers chain among its subsidiaries,
had been faced with the possibility of administration if it failed to agree
a rescheduling of loans totalling about Pounds 350m.
The group has been in discussion for several months with more than 70
international bankers. They have agreed to continue existing facilities as
an interim measure while details of the short-term financing arrangement are
being finalised.
'A lot of the spade work on that has been established. The fundamentals of
it have been agreed,' said Mr Tim Vestey, general manager of Vestey.
Mr Vestey last month handed over as Union's chief executive to Mr Terry
Robinson, formerly an executive director of Lonrho. The group had earlier
appointed Schroders as financial advisers as part of a set of proposals to
satisfy the banks that it had a viable business plan.
In return for the banks' support, the group has had forego dividend payments
on three of Union's cumulative preference stock units.
Based on the last dividend paid on the 10m shares, payment would have
amounted to about Pounds 500,000 per year, Mr Vestey said. The Vestey family
and associated trusts own about 10 per cent of the preference stocks.
Union is unlikely to publish its 1991 results until the three-year funding
facility has been agreed. Without agreement it is likely that its accounts
would be qualified.
</TEXT>
