FT  04 FEB 92 / Observer: Logic chopping
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Iraq, the glorious victor of the Gulf war in the eyes of its president at
least, has now turned its Baghdad logic on the recession in the west. Iraqi
leaders are arguing that General Motors' decision to lay off 74,000 of its
workers is the result of the economic embargo against Baghdad.
'The sanctions work both ways,' says trade minister Mohammed Mehdi Salegh.
'They have forced General Motors, for example, to lay off workers and lose
business.' His reasoning is that under a 1989 deal worth Dollars 500m, GM
was to set up a plant in Iraq to assemble 90,000 vehicles a year, which of
course hasn't happened. Hence GM's cuts.
Next: how western pressure against Iraq cost New Zealand's cricketers the
test series.
</TEXT>
