<DOCNO>FT921-10822</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CBDCGAEZFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920204
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  04 FEB 92 / Sales growth cushions traders from impact of MetroCentre
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE IMPACT of the Gateshead MetroCentre, Tyneside's out-of-town shopping
centre, on existing retail areas appears to have been softened by a general
growth in retail sales.
When the MetroCentre - Britain's first out-of-town shopping centre - opened
in 1986 there was concern that it would have a severe impact on established
shopping centres, say researchers from the Oxford Institute of Retail
Management.
Their report, monitoring the centre's first five years of operation,
indicates that although sales growth in nearby shopping centres was checked
in 1987, it generally resumed in the following two and a half years.
By June 1988, when the MetroCentre was estimated to have an annual turnover
of between Pounds 220m and Pounds 240m, it was attracting around 7 per cent
of the available retail expenditure within its 30-minute-drive catchment
area, say the researchers. By mid-1989 it employed almost 5,000 people with
46 per cent of that total full-time staff.
The report says: 'The evaluation did not show any kind of 'disaster' in
trade elsewhere, despite all the indications of changing trends.' It
estimates that between 1986 and 1989 regional retail sales increased by more
than a quarter.
However, the report cautions: 'The 1980s were exceptional in post-war times
in retail sales growth.' It also notes that the MetroCentre's impact was
more severe in weaker shopping areas.
Retail change on Tyneside and the Impact of the MetroCentre. Oxford
Institute of Retail Management, Templeton College, Kennington, Oxford OX1
5NY. Pounds 25
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
