<HEADLINE>
FT  04 FEB 92 / Parliament and Politics: Lords back amendment on religion -
Education Bill
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TWO defeats, over opportunities for religious education in sixth form
colleges and academic freedom, were inflicted on the government by the House
of Lords last night.
Dr George Carey, the archbishop of Canterbury, was supported by prominent
Conservative backbenchers as well as opposition peers on the religious
issue.
By 17 votes (106-89) they carried an amendment to the Further and Higher
Education Bill designed to ensure that the syllabus of sixth form colleges
should provide for religious education and weekly collective worship.
The government was defeated by 14 votes (86-72) on an amendment moved by
Lord Beloff (C) which curbed the powers conferred on the Education Secretary
to intervene over the appointment of higher education staff and on other
matters.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
