<HEADLINE>
FT  04 FEB 92 / Parliament and Politics: Combative Tory growler strains at
the election leash - Campaign Profile
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Conservatives have dubbed him the 'rottweiler' of their general election
campaign. The label is consciously ambiguous: a tribute to the raw
aggression he directs against the Labour party, but a less flattering
judgment also on his pugnacious temperament.
Mr David Mellor has been much in evidence on our television screens in
recent weeks, frightening voters with dire warnings of Mr Neil Kinnock's tax
plans. His weekend comment that the Labour leader had been 'craven and
cringing' towards the former Soviet Union provided a flavour of the
combative style. We will see more of him as the campaign unfolds.
He is a close friend of Mr John Major and is guaranteed promotion from his
present post as chief secretary to the Treasury if the Conservatives win the
election. It is a curious friendship. Mr Mellor's abrasive self-confidence
is the antithesis of the prime minister's careful courtesy. Among others at
Westminster, he is not widely liked.
He is bright, politically astute and effective in the brawls that pass these
days for parliamentary debates. His political instincts are those of his
master - dry on economics, wet on social policy.
Like the prime minister he is a keen supporter of Chelsea football club.
Unlike Mr Major, he is fond of eating in very expensive restaurants. He is a
gutsy politician, whose career so far has marked him out as a man who
combines vaunting ambition with a reckless confidence in his own judgment.
Mrs Margaret Thatcher, suspicious of his politics and irritated by his
imperious manner, froze him out of her cabinet.
Her demise in November 1990 provided his opportunity. He was a key figure in
Mr Major's campaign, lunching alone with the new prime minister on his first
day in No 10.
No one would describe him as one of politics' humbler souls. He can be as
publicly arrogant as he can be privately insecure. He is as rude to
officials as he is polite to a carefully cultivated coterie of journalists.
He has a keen sense of humour but finds it harder than most to laugh at
himself.
The Treasury establishment has a superiority complex, convinced that, with
occasional exceptions, mere politicians are not up to running the economy.
Mr Mellor, though, is a cherished target. Asked for an instant judgment, one
mandarin replied bluntly: 'Nigel Lawson without the intellect.'
That assessment of the 42-year-old MP for Putney is not entirely fair. He is
a clever man and a talented politician. Friends find his natural disrespect
for authority endearing.
But he cannot be surprised if a careless indifference towards those who work
for him and an ostentatious enjoyment of the trappings of ministerial office
do not attract wider admiration. As one Treasury insider comments: 'I have
never once heard him say 'thank you''.
A colleague who clashed with Mr Mellor during last year's public-spending
negotiations is more diplomatic: 'He was good, very sharp and in command of
the arguments. But he was deliberately confrontational. We wasted a lot of
time'. There were many such clashes. Mr Douglas Hurd is temperamentally as
mild as Mr Mellor is abrasive. But the foreign secretary was incensed by the
chief secretary's less than courteous negotiating style. Mr William
Waldegrave had a rougher time, storming out of one argument over his health
budget.
Nor has Mr Mellor won friends among Tory grandees. At a smart Belgravia
dinner last autumn, one of these Knights of the Shires startled the
assembled company into silence by voicing the hope that his party lost the
election. With delicious sarcasm, he explained: 'I want to see David Mellor
using the bus'.
Mr Mellor started in politics early. The son of a Wareham schoolmaster, he
was chairman of South Dorset young Conservatives at the age of 15. An
education at Cambridge and a spell at the Bar were interludes in a
determined ascent on the political escalator.
Within months of entering parliament in 1979 he was making friends among
journalists and deploying the political invective which has led Mr Major to
put him at the forefront of the Tory assault on Labour's tax plans.
By 1981 he was a junior minister at the department of energy. Subsequent
spells as a middle-ranking minister at the foreign office, the health
department, the home office (twice) and arts exposed his talents and his
flaws. Millions of television viewers saw a blistering confrontation with an
Israeli army officer over the treatment of Palestinians in Israeli-occupied
Gaza. It was an incident, a colleague says, that encapsulated neatly: 'his
personal guts and his love of the television lights'.
The brashness disguises a willingness to strike the deals essential in
politics. Skilful handling of the broadcasting bill won praise from
political opponents as well as colleagues, as he persuaded Mrs Thatcher that
quality as well as cash had a part to play in commercial television.
At the health department he fought alongside Mr Kenneth Clarke in a string
of battles with the medical professions. Others might have ducked below the
parapet.
So he has his admirers; and his unpopularity cannot be divorced from Tory
snobbery. Mr Mellor is a pushy grammar school boy in a party that does not
wholly share its leader's vision of a classless society. A sympathetic
cabinet colleague attributes the criticisms from civil servants to the
instinctive irritation of a public school establishment with ministers who
dare to set their own agenda.
He is not naturally telegenic. A chubby, gap-toothed grin and early 1970s
hairstyle are not the first choice of the image makers. He compensates with
aggression and ready wit. He intends to convince the voters that 'Dogs bark,
cats miaow and Labour puts up taxes.'
As long as he is coining phrases like that, there will be plaudits to
balance the brickbats. But Mr Mellor should be careful not to stumble. Few
colleagues will offer a hand to pull him to his feet.
</TEXT>
