<HEADLINE>
FT  04 FEB 92 / Barclaycard claims market share victory over Access
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BARCHARD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FOR the first time in two decades Barclaycard, with 8m cardholders, says it
has overtaken Access, which has more than 10.04m cardholders, in its share
of turnover in the UK credit card market.
Mr Richard Reay-Smith, chief executive of Barclays central retail services
division, said yesterday: 'This is the first time since 1979 that we have
been able to nose ahead of the four Access banks. We are gaining market
share for the first time in 20 years.'
He said that Barclaycard had 34.1 per cent of turnover in the credit card
market in the last two months of 1991, while Access, a UK MasterCard
subsidiary brand name jointly owned by National Westminster, Midland, Lloyds
and Royal Bank of Scotland, slipped back to 33.3 per cent.
Barclays has been wooing Access customers for two years by offering a rival
Barclaycard MasterCard alongside its traditional Visa products.
Mr Reay-Smith said that the introduction of an annual fee by Barclaycard had
not affected its market share. 'Strangely enough, Barclaycard has been
gaining market share since it introduced annual charges,' he said.
Access yesterday declined to comment on the figures, saying: 'We don't
believe in discussing matters affecting Barclaycard.' It added: 'Our
turnover was Pounds 11.8bn last year.'
The number of Access cards in the market has shrunk since the introduction
of charges over the past two years. Lloyds, the first bank to introduce
credit card charges, is believed to have only 1.6m Access cards compared
with about 2.8m two years ago.
With credit card profitability sharply down, all the large banks are
focusing on developing their debit card operations, and some smaller credit
card issuers have been forced to withdraw from the market. Potential buyers
are being sought for the credit card business of Town &amp; Country Building
Society after its merger with Woolwich Building Society.
Access's card processing operations were sold to First Data Resources, an
offshoot of American Express, last year. However, the four Access banks
continue to own the brand name and so far have shown no signs of dropping it
in favour of their own individual MasterCard branding.
</TEXT>
