<HEADLINE>
FT  04 FEB 92 / GrandMet charity to take over Fullemploy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CATHERINE MILTON, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GRAND Metropolitan Community Services, the training arm of the food and
drinks group, yesterday agreed in principle to take over the operations of
Fullemploy, the voluntary training organisation which caters mainly for
ethnic minorities and which went into liquidation last month.
Mr Geoffrey Bush, GMCS director, said: 'Subject to contract, we are going to
be able to continue Fullemploy's operations as previously. We hope to keep
all their centres running, either separately or linked to our own.'
Mr Aftab Pirbhai, financial director of Fullemploy, said the advantage in
the move was that both organisations had charitable status.
The takeover, due to be formally announced tomorrow, will secure the future
of Fullemploy's operations after months of uncertainty caused by a funding
crisis.
GMCS is a charity which is backed by GrandMet and has a budget of about
Pounds 3m a year. Training experts say it has a sound track record in the
field.
Recently GMCS took over South East Training, a small, London-based
organisation, which would otherwise have had to cut its places on offer.
Britain is receiving Pounds 38.7m as part of a European Community initiative
to boost job prospects. The money will be used to promote job skills
connected with the single market, the support of equal opportunities for
women in employment and vocational training, and improved work opportunities
for the mentally and physically disabled.
</TEXT>
