<HEADLINE>
FT  04 FEB 92 / Teaching attracts 92% more students
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
APPLICATIONS for teacher training places this year are running at almost
double the rate of last year, and have far exceeded provisional forecasts,
according to figures released by the Universities Central Council on
Admissions (Ucca) yesterday.
By mid December the total number of applications to universities for
teacher-training courses from this September had reached 51,412 - 92 per
cent up on the year before.
Teacher-training applications to polytechnics have risen by a similar
proportion.
The surge in applications is particularly great for prospective teachers of
maths, physics, business studies and craft, design and technology - among
the most acute shortage subjects in the 1980s.
The effect of the recession on a larger graduate market is clearly a factor.
According to the Association of Graduate Careers Advisory Services, a year
ago unemployment was running at more than 6 per cent for recent university
graduates and 10 per cent among polytechnic graduates. It is unlikely to be
much lower this year.
The increase may also be partly because of government policies aimed at
making teaching more attractive. Bursaries of between Pounds 1,500 and
Pounds 2,000 are payable to trainee teachers in shortage subjects. The
independent review body for teachers' pay is expected to recommend an
increase well above the inflation rate - in spite of a similar increase last
year.
Applications for places on other courses in higher education are also
sharply up on last year. University applications from UK residents at
188,769 show a rise of 14 per cent on last year, with polytechnic
applications at 222,559 (about 22 per cent up).
The figures exaggerate the increase, since a larger proportion of applicants
than previously have applied to both sectors. However, the rise more than
matches the 8 per cent increase in student numbers which has projected by
the government for this year compared with last year to meet its target of
one in three 18-year-olds proceeding to higher education by 2000.
Teaching apart, courses in geography, media studies, social sciences,
psychology and engineering show the biggest increases in applications to
universities.
Overseas student applications to universities are slightly down on last
year, while overseas applications to polytechnics and higher education
colleges are up by more than a third.
THE NATIONAL Union of Teachers yesterday attacked Conservative support for
the widespread return of grammar schools. It said that any attempt to revive
the selection of pupils by academic ability was the 'road to disaster'.
The call came after Education Secretary Kenneth Clarke signalled that
grammar schools would play a leading role in a more diverse education system
if the Tories won the election.
The 180,000-strong NUT said: 'Selective education failed two thirds of
children in this country. It neglected those at secondary moderns and
condemned them to second-class treatment.'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 6
</PAGE>
