<HEADLINE>
FT  04 FEB 92 / Companies fail to follow accounting guideline
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LARGE COMPANIES are continuing to use extraordinary items in their accounts
in spite of recent efforts by the Accounting Standards Board to reduce their
use.
Extraordinary items, which measure profits or losses outside normal trading
activity, are likely to be all but outlawed under a draft financial
reporting standard due to be introduced later this year.
The February report from Company Reporting, a monthly monitoring service of
company accounts based in Edinburgh, shows that at least four large British
companies have used substantial extraordinary items in their most recent
annual reports and accounts.
A statement issued by the urgent issues task force of the Accounting
Standards Board (ASB) in October warned that all the restructuring and
reorganisation costs of a business should be treated as exceptional items -
which are included in the calculation of earnings - from November 23 1991,
unless they stemmed from an extraordinary event.
All the accounts identified in Company Reporting are for 1991 financial
years ending before the new pronouncement came into force, but may have to
be restated in the next set of accounts.
Trafalgar House, the construction and shipping conglomerate, wrote off
Pounds 26.5m as an extraordinary item against Brel, the privatised train
maker, which is an associated company.
Associated British Foods, the milling and baking group, reclassified its 22
per cent stake in Berisford International as a current asset and wrote down
its value as a Pounds 100m extraordinary item.
Burton, the retailer, made an extraordinary charge of Pounds 155m,
reflecting its withdrawal from property development, on top of a similar
Pounds 169m charge in the previous year. Raglan Property Trust, the
development and investment company, counted as extraordinaries losses on a
subsidiary placed in receivership and a provision against legal action
against lenders to the subsidiary.
Company Reporting also highlights two companies that have complied with the
ASB's draft standards. Both BOC, the chemicals group, and Vaux, the hotels
and brewing group, counted business disposals as exceptional items.
The definition of extraordinary items is still under intense debate and is
likely to cause the ASB some difficulty as it tries to impose and police the
new standard.
An official for Associated British Foods said last night: 'We think our
treatment would be correct under the new and the old rules. We are whiter
than white when it comes to extraordinary and exceptional items.'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
