FT  04 FEB 92 / Late CIA chief's antiques sold: Saleroom
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTONY THORNCROFT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE ANTIQUE collection that furnished the Californian home of the late John
A. McCone, who was called in by President John F. Kennedy to head the CIA
after the Bay of Pigs fiasco, fetched Dollars 1.4m (Pounds 784,000) at
Sotheby's in New York at the weekend. Proceeds will go to an educational
foundation.
A Queen Anne scarlet japanned bureau bookcase sold for Dollars 66,000 and a
German rococo mirror of around 1750 made Dollars 44,000. Reasonable reserve
prices ensured that virtually everything sold.
Later at Sotheby's English furniture brought in Dollars 2.5m, with 20 per
cent unsold. Once again vendors were prepared to accept quite modest prices,
especially for the most important lot, a pair of George III giltwood candle
stands with candelabra. They dated to about 1770 and may have been made by
Thomas Chippendale. They sold for Dollars 82,500, well below the estimate of
Dollars 180,000-Dollars 220,000. A pair of George III giltwood pier mirrors
of about 1765 also sold below forecast, for a similar sum.
Phillips's sale of silver in London did exceptionally well, suggesting that
demand has improved considerably since Christmas. It totalled Pounds 164,990
with only 8 per cent unsold. A pair of George III wine coolers by Paul Storr
were bought by the London dealer Shrubsole for Pounds 30,800. There was also
keen bidding for silver spoons. An apostle spoon made by James Birkby in
1651 was bought by Shrubsole for Pounds 1,870.
