<HEADLINE>
FT  04 FEB 92 / UK News (Employment): TUC rules on NHS union row -
Recruitment dispute decision may rouse government anger
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE TRADES Union Congress is likely to face criticism from the government
after a TUC committee advised the FDA Civil Service union against recruiting
senior managers in the health service.
The committee said it saw no reason why other unions - including Nalgo, the
public-services union, which complained about the FDA's recruitment
intentions - should accept requests from their members to transfer to the
FDA.
The incident is politically sensitive because the government plans to
legislate to weaken the TUC's adjudication role in inter-union disputes by
giving individuals a legal right to join the union of their choice. Both the
FDA and Nalgo claimed victory after the report of the disputes committee,
which said it was unable to accept Nalgo's contention that the FDA should be
instructed not to recruit any NHS managers.
Previously the FDA's membership had been restricted to the Civil Service and
Nalgo said it would be moving into its sphere of influence by recruiting NHS
managers.
However, the committee said the introduction of a further union into the NHS
would not be helpful. It hoped the FDA would reconsider its decision.
The dispute occurred after a group among 800 general managers, some of them
Nalgo members, approached the FDA for membership. The FDA says the managers
were attracted by its offer of services to people on individual contracts.
Mr Keith Sonnet, Nalgo assistant general secretary, said his union was
concerned that recruitment among the 800 would provide the FDA with a
foothold in the NHS to recruit among 9,000 other managers. The FDA always
denied that was its intention.
The disputes committee said the FDA should cease recruitment if the
government restored the collective bargaining agreements that were withdrawn
in 1986.
The TUC would make no official comment yesterday. One union leader said the
decision showed that the disputes committee contributed towards sound
industrial relations. The London region of the TGWU general union is holding
an inquiry into alleged ballot rigging in elections for the Ford regional
automotive committee. An inquiry into alleged ballot rigging in elections
for the TGWU construction trade group is also expected soon.
</TEXT>
