FT  04 FEB 92 / UK News (Employment): Warning over works councils
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WORKS councils planned under European Community legislation constitute a
serious challenge to existing forms of union organisation in Britain,
according to an official of the International Metalworkers Federation.
The European Commission is proposing to set up works councils in larger
companies operating in more than one member state. Companies would have to
consult local works councils on matters affecting employees.
In a paper delivered yesterday at Warwick University, Mr Denis MacShane
warned: 'There is a serious dispute currently taking place about who
nominates British union representatives to Euro works councils and it is, as
yet, unresolved.'
Mr MacShane predicted that in spite of Britain's opt-out from the European
Social Chapter at the Maastricht summit, more works councils would be set up
in Britain.
Some British unions dislike the German model for works councils, under which
employees elect representatives. Those unions would prefer the appointment
of union officials.
Mr MacShane predicted that British unions would have to adapt to a
Continental system of rights for workers. He also predicted that the dispute
over representation would be settled when British unions accepted the German
model.
'For the first time in 150 years, British unions are faced with a serious
challenge not in the name of strengthening capital but in the name of
strengthening the workers,' he said.
The Trades Union Congress's organisation committee is examining how to adapt
union structures to the works council system.
</TEXT>
