</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART and RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BPCC, Britain's biggest printing group, has suffered a rash of industrial
disputes in response to the company's attempts to reduce over-capacity.
Mr George Jerome, a national official of the Graphical, Paper and Media
Union, said it was in dispute in nearly a dozen of BPCC's 44 plants over
issues including equal pay, casualisation, training and redundancy
selection.
The most serious disputes are at Pulmans in Bletchley, Buckinghamshire, and
Cromo in Nottingham, where BPCC has reverted to normal five-day-a-week,
three-shift work, having been on a six-day, four-shift system.
Both plants voted yesterday for industrial action in response to what Mr
Jerome described as a 'unilateral breach of national agreements signed in
1990'. Pulmans has about 200 union members and Cromo about 300.
Mr John Holloran, chief executive of BPCC, said that because of the
recession and overcapacity in the industry, six-day working was no longer
needed. The recession has squeezed margins but the company, which was bought
from Mr Robert Maxwell for Pounds 235m in 1989, is still expected to make a
profit this year.
