<HEADLINE>
FT  04 FEB 92 / Pay deal set to avert German steel strike
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PARKES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BONN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A DISRUPTIVE steel strike in Germany appeared to have been averted yesterday
after union leaders struck a last-ditch pay bargain with employers.
The IG Metall union urged steelworkers to accept a pay package equal to a
6.35 per cent rise in the country's first big wage settlement this year.
Members are to be asked to annul last week's overwhelming strike vote
following the weekend deal, which includes a basic 5.9 per cent
across-the-board rise and a one-off bonus of DM175 (Pounds 60.80).
The settlement straddles the 6 per cent upper limit considered the maximum
tolerable to the Bundesbank, Germany's central bank, before it can consider
reducing interest rates from their record levels.
There was concern that the agreement would encourage other unions involved
in, or about to start, their 1992 pay talks to strike in pursuit of claims
which so far are averaging 10 per cent.
Mr Rudiger Pohl, an independent economic adviser to the Bonn government,
criticised the settlement, describing it as a case of 'pilot error'.
The overall 6.35 per cent deal would set 'a standard for the whole economy',
Mr Pohl claimed. The Bundesbank would interpret such agreements as
provocation and maintain its high-interest policies, he predicted.
Mr Helmut Kaiser, head of research at Deutsche Bank, said he was glad a
strike and lost production had been avoided, and that the 'absolute pain
threshold of 6 per cent' had not been overstepped. But he was anxious the
deal should not be seen as a 'pilot settlement' for other sectors.
The agreement did little to ease tension in world markets watching the
Bundesbank for signs of relaxation of its tight grip on German money supply
and interest rates.
Although no rate cuts are expected until after the main pay deals have been
completed, bankers and governments elsewhere in the European Community had
hoped for a clearer indication of the outcome of the pay round.
Steel employers warned that the extra costs of the 'unexpectedly high'
settlement would have to be met by rationalisation. The industry is thought
to be planning to cut its 130,000 workforce by at least 6,000 this year.
Some 70,000 jobs have been lost since 1981.
The deal was hammered out in secret at an industry 'summit' at the weekend
after intervention by Mr Johannes Rau, prime minister of North Rhine
Westphalia, the north-western state where the steel industry is
concentrated.
Mr Heinz Kriwet, chairman of Thyssen, Germany's biggest steelmaker, and Mr
Franz Steinkuhler, chairman of the IG Metall union, joined talks with Mr Rau
and the two sides' chief negotiators.
According to Mr Steinkuhler, the settlement proved 'that reasonable
agreements are possible even in these economically difficult times'. It also
allowed the union to bring wages for steelworkers closer to those of their
better-paid colleagues in engineering.
Mr Klaus Murmann, head of the BDA employers' association, stressed the
importance of keeping rises below 6 per cent. The most important element in
the package for him was 'the five before the decimal point', he said.
The next confrontation over pay is expected at talks between public
employers and the OTV public services union.
