<HEADLINE>
FT  04 FEB 92 / Break-ins at MPs' offices fuel conspiracy theories
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CLAIMS that the security services may have been involved in stealing
computer data from Labour MPs' offices, yesterday fuelled pre-election
hostility and distrust at Westminster.
Labour MPs' fears that the party has been subjected to a surveillance
operation were not eased by Liberal Democrat and Conservative revelations of
burgled constituency offices.
Mr Peter Hain, Labour MP for Neath, demanded that ministers launch an
inquiry into why six Labour MPs' offices at Westminster were broken into and
computer disks or other equipment tampered with. The MPs included Mr Jack
Cunningham, Labour's campaign co-ordinator, and Mr John Prescott, the
party's transport spokesman.
'Who could have been interested in the Labour party's plans and strategy in
the run-up to the general election? I think the answer can only be either
the intelligence services supplying the Government or the Conservative
party,' Mr Hain said on BBC radio.
Mr Cunningham said there was 'no evidence' pointing to any particular
organisation being responsible for the break-ins. 'I have made no political
accusations and I am not responsible for the story emerging in the first
place.'
In spite of the Labour leadership's refusal to become involved and the scorn
ministers poured on conspiracy theories, the allegations added to a frenzy
of smear and counter-smear, sometimes bordering on the farcical.
The allegations come at the start of what could become Britain's dirtiest
general election campaign, with Labour and the Tories neck and neck in the
opinion polls.
At the weekend there were Labour claims of a Tory-inspired smear over
opposition party links with the Kremlin in the early 1980s.
Mr John MacGregor, leader of the Commons, dismissed suggestions of a
political intelligence operation as 'nonsense' and 'symptomatic of the kind
of hysteria that seems to have built up on the Labour side.' Only one
break-in at Westminster had been reported to the Commons' authorities, he
said. Conservative Central Office officials, however, confirmed last night
that constituency offices in some marginal seats had been burgled in the
past year.  Computer equipment and a microwave oven were stolen from the
office of Bath MP, Mr Chris Patten, party chairman.
The Liberal Democrats' election strategist, Mr Des Wilson, called for a
tri-party pact to concentrate on issues, not smears. Asked about the
burglaries, he said: 'I don't know and I don't care'.
Party officials later said that constituency offices at Littleborough and
Saddleworth had been broken into at the weekend and computer equipment
stolen. Membership lists had also been stolen over the past year from the
constituency offices of Mr Richard Livsey, MP for Brecon and Radnor, and Mr
Matthew Taylor, MP for Truro.
Last September, the membership list of the Liberal Democrats' councillors'
association, stored on a hard computer disk in offices in Hebden Bridge,
Yorkshire, was also stolen.
Parliament, Page 8
Lang calls on Scots, Page 16
</TEXT>
